### Step[8]
Analysis: We followed the required preprocess->anomaly detection->fault identification->root-cause-localization workflow using metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. Key facts from the executed steps: 
- Metrics: many container KPIs referencing 'container.node-5.container_network_receive_*' spiked within the incident window; TCP retransmission (system.net.tcp.retrans_segs) spikes were also observed on nodes. A per-component severity ranking showed the single largest deviation (max_over_p95_ratio ≈ 8589×) at checkoutservice-2 (pod-level), with many other pods on node-5 also showing elevated container.node-5 network-receive KPIs.
- Traces: extremely large latency spikes were localized to frontend ⇄ checkoutservice call paths, notably frontend-2 ↔ checkoutservice-2, with earliest anomalous trace points at ~2022-03-21 20:03:00 CST (Asia/Shanghai).
- Logs: error_logs and log.csv show frontends produced many warnings starting at 20:00:00 CST and substantial log.error_count for frontend-0/1/2 in the 20:00–20:06 window; checkoutservice logs show no corresponding error_count. Frontend warnings state failures to retrieve responses from backends.
- Topology mapping: both checkoutservice-2 and frontend-2 have metrics tied to node-5 (they appear among cmdb_ids with 'container.node-5' KPIs), so the impacted pods are colocated on node-5.
Reasoning to root cause: the largest metric deviation is at the pod-level (checkoutservice-2) and it is the downstream service in the trace call chain where severe latency appears. Numerous container metrics indicate network receive spikes associated with node-5 and TCP retransmissions appear on nodes as well, while frontends show retrieval failures in logs. According to the diagnosis rules, when the greatest deviation is at the container/pod level and traces/logs indicate that pod is the downstream faulty component, the root cause should be the container/pod. Correlating earliest anomalous trace points and node-5 container network spikes yields the earliest practical occurrence time of the failure.

Instruction: Root cause summary (final answer):
- Root cause component: checkoutservice-2 (pod).
- Root cause occurrence datetime (Asia/Shanghai): 2022-03-21 20:03:00 CST (approximate onset of the anomalous traces/metrics).
- Root cause reason: severe container-network receive degradation on the node hosting that pod (node-5) — manifested as abnormally high container.node-5.network_receive metrics and correlated TCP retransmissions and packet-level network issues — causing high latency for frontend→checkoutservice requests and frontend-side "failed to retrieve" warnings.

Confidence & notes:
- Confidence: high (trace latency spikes, extreme per-pod metric deviation at checkoutservice-2, node-5 network receive spikes across many pods, and frontend logs all align).
- The incident likely originated from network-level packet loss/congestion on node-5 that impacted checkoutservice-2 (downstream) and caused frontend request failures/latency beginning ~20:03 CST. Recommended follow-ups: inspect node-5 network interface, host-level networking (queues/iodrops), and underlying physical/virtual NIC or host networking stack for packet loss; correlate specific trace request IDs between frontend warnings and checkoutservice-2 spans for definitive end-to-end proof.
